1 Quando colui che tutto ’l mondo alluma 2 de l’emisperio nostro sì discende, 3 che ’l giorno d’ogne parte si consuma,
4 lo ciel, che sol di lui prima s’accende, 5 subitamente si rifà parvente 6 per molte luci, in che una risplende;
7 e questo atto del ciel mi venne a mente, 8 come ’l segno del mondo e de’ suoi duci 9 nel benedetto rostro fu tacente;
10 però che tutte quelle vive luci, 11 vie più lucendo, cominciaron canti 12 da mia memoria labili e caduci.

query.result:
**English:**
1 When he who lights up the whole world 2 descends from our hemisphere, 3 so that daylight fades on every side,
4 the sky, which was lit up by him alone before, 5 suddenly becomes visible again 6 through many lights, in which one shines brightly;
7 and this act of the sky came to my mind, 8 as the sign of the world and its leaders 9 was silent in the blessed beak;
10 because all those living lights, 11 shining more brightly, began songs 12 that are faint and fleeting in my memory.
**Old English:**
1 Þonne se ðe ealne ðisne middangeard 2 of ðissum heofonhringum hweorfeð niðer, 3 ðæt ðæs dæges leoht of ðære lyfte gewiteð,
4 ðonne bið ðæs rodores hrof geworht 5 ðurh ða monigfealdan steorran, ðær ðara sum scyneð;
6 and ðeos gesceaft ðæs heofontungles 7 me ða on mode wearð, 8 swa swa ðæs middangeardes and ðara heretogena 9 on ðam halgan fugle wæs ðæt tacen geswegen;
10 forðæm ðe ða lybban leoht ealle 11 beorhtor scinende song ongunnon, 12 ðe min gemynd ða gearo ne mæg.

